dt.t: Corinne, who was the smallest {wi}quint{/wi} at birth—2 pounds, 14 ounces—is still the shortest.
The natural birth rate for twins is 1 in 90; for {wi}quints{/wi} it's around 1 in 65 million.

dt: {bc}a jump (as in figure skating or skiing) that consists of at least five but less than six revolutions

dt.t: … a Czech named Ales Valenta revolutionized the sport of freestyle aerials yesterday with a magical {wi}quint{/wi}, five twists that earned him a spectacular score …

Goebel … had already become the first U.S. skater to land a {d_link|quad|quad:3} at the nationals … making them look so easy that his coach, Carol Heiss Jenkins, spoke of Goebel's someday doing a "{wi}quint{/wi}."

dt: {bc}a multi-purpose vehicle used by firefighters that includes a water tank, {d_link|fire hose|fire hose}, pump, aerial ladder or platform, and portable ladders

dt.t: Firefighters call it a "{wi}quint{/wi}" because it combines five different functions, [David] Kinsey said. The truck carries a ladder, a hose, a pump with its own generator, a 400-gallon water tank and a 100-foot-long aerial tower.

Over the next couple of years, aging engine and ladder trucks at the 10 lower-activity stations will be replaced with {wi}quints{/wi}—fire trucks that carry ladders, water tank, pump, hoses and other rescue and fire suppression equipment.
